Item currently only has a single toString() method, which prints name and quantity.

We may want different interpretations of Item in differente contexts, e.g. Edit and Search

- Change the implementation accordingly in Edit and Search to use toDetailedString

Previously, SearchCommand used its output for JUnit tests.

It is not very robust.

A List<Item> results is implemented instead to represent the returned items for commands that do not modify ItemList. Examples are list and search.

More tests could be done to verify the printing functionality. However, the new implementation suffices in checking that the order of selected Items are correct.

commitResults.messageBody:
EditCommand clones an Item and edits its fields. If no errors arise, the new Item will replace the old Item.
However, the clone was a shallow copy done manually.

A deep copy is required to maintain the BorrowRecords associated with
Item.

Let's
- Implement a clone() in Item that does a deep copy
- Replace the cloning method in EditCommand to use Item's clone() method.

Add LocalDate TypeAdapter to Gson serializer and deserializer.
commitResults.messageBody:
GSON used Reflection to access the field types of LocalDate objects.
This results in Java showing us a warning message regarding illegal reflective access.

To resolve this, we must pass a TypeAdapter to the Gson object used to serialize and deserialize our JSON.

Let's
- Make a TypeAdapter to customise serialisation/deserialisation of java.util.LocalDate
- Register this TypeAdapter with the Gson objects in Storage

Fixes #83
Fixes #134

commitResults.messageBody:
Java, by default, adds references of objects into arraylist. This means the original Items in ItemList may be modified.

This may result in a race condition! Each test are given their own threads to execute in JUnit.

To fix this, we should clone the Item and add them to the list before returning the itemlist.

Let's
- Implement clone() for BorrowRecord, needed for deep copying
- Implement a deep copy of Item() in its clone method to clone BorrowRecord
- Change ItemListStubs to generate new mutable ItemLists that are clones of the specified Items.

align with the User Guide where we should be able to.

and use that list to check if we should return a message saying that
there are no records.

no items in the item list.

name of the item)

there are any borrowings at all
* Modify remaining code to utilise the list of records created, rather
than creating another list for the sake of printing
